{"response":{"status":"ok","userTier":"internal","total":1,"content":{"webTitle":"Is Obama's climate plan enough to 'stop the planet being beyond fixing'?","webPublicationDate":"2013-06-26T15:32:27Z","sectionName":"Environment","sectionId":"environment","id":"environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/25/1372192060112/Obama-climate-change-spee-005.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3gpg9","displayHint":"news","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-643cb134-ff45-4e29-abf3-48b7eaa0cfcf\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/25/1372189113385/Obama-Gives-Major-Speech--011.jpg\" alt=\"Obama Gives Major Speech On Climate Change\" width=\"620\" height=\"372\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Barack Obama speaks as he unveils his plan on climate change at Georgetown University in Washington DC. Photograph: Alex Wong/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure>","standfirst":"Barack Obama has laid out his 'climate action plan', but will it be enough to halt the rise in carbon emissions? Leo Hickman, with your help, investigates. Post your views below, email <a href=\"mailto:leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk\">leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk</a> or tweet <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/leohickman\">@LeoHickman</a>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2013-06-26T16:36:35.731+01:00","firstPublicationDate":"2013-06-26T09:51:19.131+01:00","body":"<div id=\"block-51cb058fe4b0a53e53280c8d\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-06-26T16:32:27.157+01:00\">4.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">My verdict</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Obama, as ever, scored highly on inspiring rhetoric. For some, this was the most important aspect of his speech, given how little to date his presidency has offered the so-called \"climate concerned\". He gave the strong impression that climate change was back, square and centre, on the Oval Office desk, something he had promised on the election trail, both in 2008 and 2012.</p> <p>But details matter when it comes to climate and energy policies. And details were lacking in his speech. We still don't know, for example, what he intends to do with the Keystone pipeline. What does he mean by \"significantly\" when he says he will authorise it, but only if it \"does not significantly exacerbate the climate problem\"? And without instruments such as carbon taxes and \"cap and trade\", how can we be sure that his beloved shale gas only ever replaces coal and not, as some fear, also curtails growth in renewables?</p> <p>And what of the wider question of whether the US's current emissions targets are enough to help prevent global temperatures rising above 2C over the course of this century? Judging by the calculations of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">Prof Piers Forster</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cafaa9e4b0e2a9937599df\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, it would appear the current targets are woefully short of where they need to be. But, if we're being honest, we already knew that.</p> <p>Therefore, Obama's speech can certainly be spun&nbsp;positively as \"better late than never\", but a pragmatic assessment must conclude that the US is still making baby steps when huge strides forward are required. This is not the global leadership so many wish the US to take on climate change.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51cafaa9e4b0e2a9937599df\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-06-26T15:28:57.910+01:00\">3.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Reacting to the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">earlier analysis</a> by Prof Piers Forster, <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/faculty/hopec.html\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, a climate change policy researcher and PAGE model developer at the <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/\">University of Cambridge Judge Business School</a>, has sent me his <a href=\"http://www.chrishopepolicy.com/2013/06/how-much-will-the-world-benefit-from-obamas-climate-plan/\">own calculations</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Piers Forster made <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">some initial calculations</a> that a 17% drop in US emissions by 2020 could reduce CO2 concentrations in 2100 by between 3 and 5 ppm, and reduce temperature rises by between 0.02C and 0.04C compared to where they would be without the US plan. But Piers&rsquo;s calculation used just a single value for equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS) of 3C.</p> <p>The PAGE09 model (<a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/working_papers/2011/wp1104.pdf\">pdf</a>) uses a range of climate sensitivities consistent with the latest IPCC reports. Running Obama&rsquo;s plan to reduce US emissions by 17% by 2020 through 10,000 runs of the PAGE09 model confirms that, with a range of ECS values, the plan will reduce global mean temperatures by between 0.012C and 0.032C by 2100 (5-95% values), with a most likely reduction of 0.02C, compared to business as usual. The PAGE09 model can also do what Piers could not, and make an estimate of how much this drop in temperatures would reduce global damages from climate change. The answer is it will reduce them by between 0.5 and 10.5 trillion dollars (5-95% values), with a mean reduction in damage of 4.5 trillion dollars.</p> <p>As <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/25/obama-climate-speech-expert-verdict\">other commentators have said</a>, it&rsquo;s a start.</p> <p>(Details: US CO2 emissions assumed to be 17% below base year (2008) emissions from 2020 until 2075. Comparison with IPCC A1B business as usual scenario.)</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51cae3aee4b02dad15c7494e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-06-26T13:51:12.734+01:00\">1.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/25/obama-tries-the-kitchen-sink-approach-to-global-warming/?e\">Brad Plumer's analysis</a> on the Washington Post's Wonkblog is worth a read:</p> <blockquote> <p>If you take a look around the world, averting climate change looks like a daunting task.&nbsp;Global emissions <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/carbon-dioxide-emissions-rose-14-percent-in-2012-iea-report-says/2013/06/09/35d32bac-d123-11e2-8cbe-1bcbee06f8f8_story.html\">soared to record levels</a> last year. The World Bank&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2012/11/19/were-on-pace-for-4c-of-global-warming-heres-why-the-world-bank-is-terrified/\">is warning</a>&nbsp;that the Earth is on pace to heat up more than 2&deg;C by century&rsquo;s end, and possibly&nbsp;as much as 4&deg;C&nbsp;(7.2&deg;F) if the worst-case scenarios pan out &mdash; a level, it says, that humanity might be unable to adapt to. And international climate talks are barely limping along.</p> <p>For now, then, the minimum that the United States can do is try to meet the near-term climate goals that Obama promised as part of the Copenhagen Accord a few years back. That would require reducing U.S. emissions 17 percent below 2005 levels by 2020. Right now, the country isn&rsquo;t on pace to do that:</p> </blockquote>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-45e23860-fc40-4c47-80c2-ed0e13a2d526\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250962466/d79ba6a6-60e0-45b2-ad90-a681473ce5e2-460x276.png\" alt=\"US energy-related CO2 emissions, 1973-2040\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>US energy-related CO2 emissions, 1973-2040 Photograph: Washington Post</figcaption> </figure>  <blockquote> <p>Since 2005, U.S. energy-related carbon-dioxide emissions have fallen about 11.8 percent,* thanks to the recession, improved energy-efficiency, and a shift from coal to natural gas. But those trends have bottomed out recently, and coal started <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/05/28/coal-is-making-a-comeback-in-2013/\">making a comeback in 2013</a>. The White House <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/03/15/how-the-white-house-thinks-about-climate-change-in-7-charts/\">has argued</a> that new &ldquo;policy steps&rdquo; will be necessary to get back on track.</p> <p>Four years ago, the White House was hoping that Congress would write a big climate bill to enforce these emissions cuts. That policy, known as &ldquo;cap-and-trade,&rdquo; would have set an economy-wide ceiling on U.S. greenhouse-gas emissions and allowed businesses to trade pollution permits with each other in order to stay under the ceiling. But the climate bill died in the Senate in the summer of 2010.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51caccfee4b049e62ebabe9b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-06-26T12:14:06.595+01:00\">12.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Meanwhile, on the other side of the \"pond\", the UK government's Committee on Climate Change has published its annual report. And it's not good news, as Fiona Harvey <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/jun/26/uk-miss-carbon-emissions-targets\">reports in the Guardian</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>The UK is on track to miss its carbon targets in the 2020s, the government's advisers on <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/climate-change\">climate change</a> warned on Wednesday.</p> <p>Efforts to cut emissions are not happening quickly enough, and a looming \"policy gap\" will lead to a shortfall in the investment and infrastructure needed for a <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sustainable-business/low-carbon?INTCMP=SRCH\">low-carbon economy</a>, they said.</p> <p>Last year, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/mar/28/uk-co2-emissions-up-2012\"> UK greenhouse gas emissions rose by 3.5%</a>, in a setback to the government's plans for stringent \"carbon budgets\" that stipulate steep falls in emissions from now to 2027. The rise was owing to the cold winter and more power coming from coal, which is currently cheap.</p> <p>The <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/committee-on-climate-change?INTCMP=SRCH\">committee on climate change</a>, in its annual progress report, said this was a temporary increase and the UK was likely to meet its carbon reduction goals for 2017. But it warned that without strong measures the UK would miss its carbon reduction targets from 2017 to 2027. When the effects of last year's rise are stripped out, the underlying emissions trend is for a 1% to 1.5% decrease in emissions each year &ndash; less than half the 3% annual reductions needed to meet longer-term climate goals.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51cacb41e4b049e62ebabe95\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-06-26T12:07:15.875+01:00\">12.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Twitter reaction</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/James_BG/statuses/349814585571803136\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Important point in Obama speech that has not picked up much coverage - he calls on people to divest from fossil fuels <a href=\"http://t.co/bvS4TQ58n2\">http://t.co/bvS4TQ58n2</a></p>&mdash; James Murray (@James_BG) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/James_BG/statuses/349814585571803136\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/TheAtlantic/statuses/349814496417693697\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Why Obama&#39;s Climate Change Plan Is Hopeless Without China <a href=\"http://t.co/CgYFut6ig4\">http://t.co/CgYFut6ig4</a></p>&mdash; The Atlantic (@TheAtlantic) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheAtlantic/statuses/349814496417693697\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/insideclimate/statuses/349782307726561280\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Obama tries to breathe life into <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23climate&amp;src=hash\">#climate</a> agenda that has slipped from his control. Analysis of his big speech/plan: <a href=\"http://t.co/EeDrLzu6Zs\">http://t.co/EeDrLzu6Zs</a></p>&mdash; InsideClimate News (@insideclimate) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/insideclimate/statuses/349782307726561280\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/eilperin/statuses/349715230378573826\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>After all the build-up, Obama delivered a full-throated endorsement of climate action. Here&#39;s my take: <a href=\"http://t.co/P75FVEA4gf\">http://t.co/P75FVEA4gf</a></p>&mdash; Juliet Eilperin (@eilperin) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/eilperin/statuses/349715230378573826\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/MarcGunther/statuses/349701787596492800\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>&quot;Bowels of the bureaucracy&quot;: An excellent analysis by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drgrist\">@drgrist</a> of Obama&#39;s <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23climate&amp;src=hash\">#climate</a> speech <a href=\"http://t.co/p6sXWnDsMr\">http://t.co/p6sXWnDsMr</a></p>&mdash; Marc Gunther (@MarcGunther) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MarcGunther/statuses/349701787596492800\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/campbellclaret/statuses/349679171523461121\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Thank heavens Obama trying to get climate change back on global agenda. About time, and time others did same</p>&mdash; Alastair Campbell (@campbellclaret) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/campbellclaret/statuses/349679171523461121\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/NewYorker/statuses/349678943277809665\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Elizabeth Kolbert on Obama&#39;s overdue <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23climate&amp;src=hash\">#climate</a>-change speech and how it is better late than never: <a href=\"http://t.co/hXqkWnJkUm\">http://t.co/hXqkWnJkUm</a></p>&mdash; The New Yorker (@NewYorker) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/NewYorker/statuses/349678943277809665\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EliasHinckley/statuses/349838177734889473\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Read this: <a href=\"https://twitter.com/nelderini\">@nelderini</a> looking at the data on Obama&#39;s new climate plan  <a href=\"http://t.co/wWGUhPuFHA\">http://t.co/wWGUhPuFHA</a> spoiler: he&#39;s underwhelmed</p>&mdash; Elias Hinckley (@EliasHinckley) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EliasHinckley/statuses/349838177734889473\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/TIME/statuses/349844684681641984\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-twee