e","width":"620"}}]},{"id":"_no_ids","relation":"body","type":"embed","assets":[{"type":"embed","file":"http://www.scribd.com/doc/145639278/Tim-Yeo-MP-energy-bill-amendment-speech","typeData":{"source":"Scribd","description":"Tim Yeo MP energy bill amendment speech - Free download as PDF File (.pdf), Word Doc (.doc / .docx), Text File (.txt) or readfalse online for free. Tim Yeo MP energy bill amendment speech, House of Commons, 04/06/2013","credit":"Jane Crinnion","title":"Tim Yeo MP energy bill amendment speech","embedType":"document"}}]},{"id":"gu-fc-90760465-fe07-418b-81f9-a35811e2f0b3","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/11/7/1352325578455/83b333eb-e509-49e5-afcb-3fb0db7b0769-140.jpeg","typeData":{"secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/11/7/1352325578455/83b333eb-e509-49e5-afcb-3fb0db7b0769-140.jpeg","source":"PA","photographer":"David Parry","altText":"A birds eye view of the official launch of Ice Rink  in Canada Square Park, Canary Wharf, London, where a team of British Championship medalists and members of the International Development Squad skaters cut the ice.","height":"84","credit":"David Parry/PA","caption":"A birds eye view of the official launch of Ice Rink  in Canada Square Park, Canary Wharf, London, where a team of British Championship medalists and members of the International Development Squad skaters cut the ice.  Photograph: David Parry/PA","mediaId":"gu-fc-90760465-fe07-418b-81f9-a35811e2f0b3","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"How much are UK green policies adding to energy bills?","webPublicationDate":"2013-07-16T16:46:00Z","sectionName":"Environment","sectionId":"environment","id":"environment/blog/2013/jul/16/green-policies-energy-bills-climate","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/3/23/1364032919148/-Cheyne-Court-Wind-Farm-o-005.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3hba5","displayHint":"news","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-00f6b17d-db97-4361-aebd-bdfe5d7bab50\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/3/23/1364032926321/-Cheyne-Court-Wind-Farm-o-011.jpg\" alt=\" Cheyne Court Wind Farm on Romney Marsh, Kent.  \" width=\"620\" height=\"372\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A general view from Camber Sands in East Sussex of the Cheyne Court Wind Farm on Romney Marsh, Kent.   Photograph: Gareth Fuller/PA</figcaption> </figure>","standfirst":"RWE npower says bills will rise £240 by 2020 due to green policies. Leo Hickman, with your help, investigates. Post your views below, email <a href=\"mailto:leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk\">leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk</a> or tweet <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/leohickman\">@LeoHickman</a>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2013-07-17T11:18:45.241+01:00","firstPublicationDate":"2013-07-16T12:45:18.442+01:00","body":"<div id=\"block-51e574c7e4b0c5ca8f2d5432\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T17:46:09.386+01:00\">5.46pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">My verdict</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Today's report by RWE npower is to be welcomed for the simple reason that it gives us some more numbers to work with in the - let's be honest - near-futile game of trying to estimate what our energy bills will be in 2020 and beyond. No one knows with certainty - despite what they might tell you - what the price of oil, gas, nuclear, etc, is going to be a decade from now. Therefore, all such assumptions and projections must be viewed with a degree of scepticism and perspective.</p> <p>The battles between Decc and its critics over the cost of its low-carbon energy policies will no doubt continue, but the report performs the important task of breaking down our energy bills into categories. Personally, I would like to see this information shown on energy bills today and I join those in calling for more transparency for consumers about the various components that make energy the price is it today.</p> <p>The UKERC report clearly shows that there is plenty of support for the government's low-carbon energy policies, but this could be undermined if the public is shielded from the costs. Honesty will also help to muffle those who try to claim - as has been seen today in some reporting of RWE npower's report - that bill rises are all down to green policies. The report shows that not to be true. What it does do is breakdown the individual costs of various green policies today, as well as other factors, which can only be useful.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e5753be4b0d403fb03badb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T17:30:51.347+01:00\">5.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Mike Landy, senior policy analyst at the <a href=\"http://www.r-e-a.net/\">Renewable Energy Association</a>, has sent me his thoughts:</p> <blockquote> <p>The truth is nobody really knows how exactly how quickly fossil fuel costs are going to rise. Neither do we know exactly how quickly renewable energy costs are going to fall. But we do know that both these things have been happening historically and we can expect that to continue into the future. Solar PV and onshore wind have shown particularly impressive cost reductions in recent years as their markets has developed, while world energy demand and the cost of fossil extraction continue to increase &ndash; and that&rsquo;s without accounting for the huge environmental costs of fossil fuels. At some point those two lines will cross &ndash; the so-called grid parity point for power.&nbsp;Thereafter the cost case in favour of the renewable option becomes increasingly compelling as time goes on.</p> <p>The only uncertainty is exactly when the cross-over will take place.&nbsp;A subsidy is required in the run-up to the cross-over, but after that the marginal energy price is set by the renewable option, providing a ceiling against which everything else will be compared.&nbsp;That day is getting closer and closer &ndash; we just need a bit a patience and perseverance!</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e57097e4b0d403fb03bad9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T17:11:04.081+01:00\">5.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The <a href=\"http://www.ukerc.ac.uk/support/article3045\">new report</a> by the UK Energy Research Centre is certainly worth a read. The report's authors asked 1,800 respondents to complete <a href=\"http://my2050.decc.gov.uk/\">Decc's My2050 tool</a>, which allows each user to create their own energy \"pathway\" using a combination of 14 different energy options to reduce UK emissions by 80% by 2050. The results are shown from page 11 onwards:</p> <blockquote> <p>The British public wants to see a reduction in fossil fuel use over the next few decades with a substantial majority believing that a future energy system primarily reliant on fossil fuels is unacceptable. There is very little variability in this opinion reflecting a core aspiration to transition away from fossil fuel energy to renewable forms. We note that 80% of respondents significantly reduced fossil fuels (selecting either levels 2 or 3 in the online tool) in their My2050 pathways.</p> <p>Fossil fuels are seen as polluting, archaic, finite and particularly in the case of oil are associated with global conflicts. There is some evidence that these concerns extend to unconventional fossil fuels such as shale gas.</p> <p>Gas shows some nuances in terms of public preferences, where it is evaluated more positively than oil and coal, particularly in the context of personal use of gas central heating.</p> <p>Among the British public we find a strong preference for a shift to renewable energy systems and a corresponding move away from fossil fuels. This is a relatively clear and stable preference in the sense that renewables are always the preferred way of supplying energy for a large majority of people. Nearly 80% of respondents included high levels of offshore wind energy and other renewables in their My2050 pathways.</p> </blockquote> <p>Given the perception - stoked by some quarters of the media and certain politicians - that there is widespread public hostility to wind power, it is interesting to see that the report's findings strongly contradict this view:</p> <blockquote> <p>&bull; Wind energy is viewed favourably by a majority of the British public, in line with a desire to move to a renewable energy system. As such, wind energy plays a key role in public energy pathways with significant support for both onshore and offshore wind farms.<br />&bull; We find higher levels of support for offshore wind farms compared to onshore wind farms.<br />&bull; Publics recognise that wind energy is a technology ready to be deployed at scale. Findings also indicate under-estimation of the extent to which wind energy can contribute to electricity generation in the UK.<br />&bull; There are mixed views on whether wind farms spoil the landscape, or are good for nearby communities.<br />&bull; In line with other research, our findings indicate that support for wind energy cannot be taken-for-granted. There is a need to pay close attention to the siting of wind farms, e.g. in terms of locations, ownership, and fair process.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e567dfe4b0d403fb03bace\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T16:33:51.559+01:00\">4.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>In addition to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jul/16/green-policies-energy-bills-climate#block-51e557a4e4b0301f54015405\">Ed Davey's comments</a> reported by BusinessGreen, a spokesman at Decc has also sent me the department's reaction to some of the assumptions and calculations made by RWE npower in its report:</p> <blockquote> <ul> <li>We believe energy efficiency policies (Energy Company Obligation) currently cost around &pound;400m less than Npower claims and their estimate for 2020 is nearly double ours.</li> <li>Npower fails to take into account the impact of energy efficiency policies - they include all of the costs but none of the savings. Already 2.4m wall cavities, 4.9m lofts and 88,000 solid walls have been insulated since April 2008 - saving &pound;25-&pound;270 per installation per year. By 2022 half of all households are expected to have at least one insulation measure delivered through supplier obligations, plus potentially more through the green deal.</li> <li>Npower claims commodity and production costs will fall from &pound;565 now to &pound;514 in 2020. We think it is more likely that fossil fuel prices will continue to rise. Our central gas price projection suggests an increase of 5% between now and 2020.</li> <li>Npower significantly overestimate the cost of smart meters to the average consumer and do not take into account that they will help households save energy.</li> </ul> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e55a20e4b0a87873a7b7a8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T15:36:24.439+01:00\">3.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Reader reaction</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>In addition to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jul/16/green-policies-energy-bills-climate#block-51e557a4e4b0301f54015405\">Ed Davey's comments</a> reported by BusinessGreen, a spokesman at Decc has also just sent me the department's reaction to some of the assumptions and calculations made by RWE npower in its report:</p> <blockquote> <ul> <li>We believe energy efficiency policies (Energy Company Obligation) currently cost around &pound;400m less than Npower claims and their estimate for 2020 is nearly double ours.</li> <li>Npower fails to take into account the impact of energy efficiency policies - they include all of the costs but none of the savings. Already 2.4m wall cavities, 4.9m lofts and 88,000 solid walls have been insulated since April 2008 - saving &pound;25-&pound;270 per installation per year. By 2022 half of all households are expected to have at least one insulation measure delivered through supplier obligations, plus potentially more through the green deal.</li> <li>Npower claims commodity and production costs will fall from &pound;565 now to &pound;514 in 2020. We think it is more likely that fossil fuel prices will continue to rise. Our central gas price projection suggests an increase of 5% between now and 2020.</li> <li>Npower significantly overestimate the cost of smart meters to the average consumer and do not take into account that they will help households save energy.</li> </ul> </blockquote>  <figure class=\"element element-comment\" data-canonical-url=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/comment-permalink/25183374\">  <div class=\"d2-comment-embedded\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Comment\"> <div class=\"d2-left-col\"> <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/10908627\" title=\"View planktonmath’s profile\"> <img class=\"d2-avatar\" src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif\" height=\"40\" width=\"40\" alt=\"User avatar for planktonmath\"> </a> </div> <div class=\"d2-right-col\"> <div itemscope itemprop=\"author\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\"> <a class=\"d2-username\" href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/10908627\" title=\"View planktonmath’s profile\" itemprop=\"url\"> <span itemprop=\"givenName\">planktonmath</span> </a> </div> <div class=\"d2-permalink\"> <a class=\"d2-datetime\" href=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/comment-permalink/25183374\" title=\"Link to this comment\" itemprop=\"datePublished\">16 July 2013 1:24pm</a> </div> <div class=\"d2-body\" itemprop=\"text\"><p>There are two key issues here. One is whether gas prices will continue to increase resulting in bills going up. The other is whether electricity from renewables will be more expensive than that from gas.</p> <p>The answer to the first question is rather obvious: we do not know, and really should not pretend to know on the basis of what we want to be true. There are things that could exert significant download force on gas prices, Japan returning to nuclear and reducing it's liquified natural gas imports and the export of LNG from the US. But the impact of these things is far from clear, and our views on renewable energy have rather little to do with it.</p> <p>The answer to the second question however seems much clearer. Electricity from renewables will almost certainly be more expensive than renewables this decade. After all the cost of offshore wind is almost three times higher than the cost of electricity from gas.</p> <p>These realities hint at an obvious conclusion. You need to convince the public that they should pay extra for low carbon energy, whether it is renewables or nuclear. If we allow this issue to be framed purely in terms of keeping bills down there is probably only one result: fossil fuels will win.</p> <p><a rel=\"nofollow\">Robert Wilson</a></p></div> </div> </div>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-comment\" data-canonical-url=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/comment-permalink/25186884\">  <div class=\"d2-comment-embedded\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Comment\"> <div class=\"d2-left-col\"> <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/3990813\" title=\"View MurchuantEacnamai’s profile\"> <img class=\"d2-avatar\" src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif\" height=\"40\" width=\"40\" alt=\"User avatar for MurchuantEacnamai\"> </a> </div> <div class=\"d2-right-col\"> <div itemscope itemprop=\"author\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\"> <a class=\"d2-username\" href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/3990813\" title=\"View MurchuantEacnamai’s profile\" itemprop=\"url\"> <span itemprop=\"givenName\">MurchuantEacnamai</span> </a> </div> <div class=\"d2-permalink\"> <a class=\"d2-datetime\" href=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/comment-permalink/25186884\" title=\"Link to this comment\" itemprop=\"datePublished\">16 July 2013 3:06pm</a> </div> <div class=\"d2-body\" itemprop=\"text\"><p>In his rebuttal of the Taxpayers' Alliance claims Secretary Of State Davey asserts that &quot;It’s the global gas price, not green subsidies, that has primarily been pushing up energy bills. 60% of the increase in household energy bills between 2010 and 2012 was caused by this.&quot;</p> <p>This is true, but global gas prices rose following the post-Fukushima nuclear shut-in in Japan massively increased Japan's demand for gas. DECC's central gas price projections - on which much of its future energy bill calculations are made - assume increasing gas prices. A combination of factors - DG COMP finally investigating Gazprom's over-pricing of gas, the re-activation of Japan's nuclear plant, massive reserves of gas off east Africa, the reluctance of India and China to pay current prices, the slow approval of US LNG export projects - all presage of softening of gas prices. </p> <p>However, irrespective of future gas prices, DECC has decided to pay offshore wind £155/MWh (declining over 5 years to £135). This will avoid the emission of approx. 0.4 tonne of CO2 - giving an implicit price of £387.5/tCO2 (net of other costs and benefits which tend to balance out)</p> <p>Currently, low-priced coal is displacing gas in electricity generation not only in Britain, but throughout the EU. It isn't straight forward to estimate the EU ETS emission allowance (EUA) price that would be required to force a switch from coal to gas - I would be interested in readers' estimates, but it is likely to be considerably less than £387.5/tCO2.</p> <p>This is not to say that gas is a long term solution, but, when CO2 emissions from Britain's electricity sector are increasing, it suggests that SoS Davey might be better employed working with his EU counterparts to get the EU ETS working properly, to make the EU's internal market work more effectively so as to put pressure on external suppliers and to faciliate the free trade agreement with the US which will faciliate more US gas exports, increase gas prices there and reduce the supply of low-priced coal.</p> <p>Lower gas prices will be able to bear a much higher EUA price, drive dirty coal out of electricity generation and provide the incentive for efficient renewables - and, potentially, the incentive for widespread use of CCS.</p> <p>The only problem is that the 'save the planet at all costs brigade' would go mad and the LibDems are counting on their support to avoid electoral melt-down.</p></div> </div> </div>  </figure> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T16:12:57.077+01:00\">at 4.12pm BST</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51e557a4e4b0301f54015405\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T15:24:36.980+01:00\">3.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>BusinessGreen has the <a href=\"http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2282743/ed-davey-slams-ridiculous-npower-energy-bill-projections\">first reaction</a> from Ed Davey, the energy and climate secretary, to RWE npowers' report - and it isn't positive:</p> <blockquote> <p>Speaking to <em>BusinessGreen </em>as part of a wide-ranging interview to be published later this week, Davey criticised npower's methodology and questioned its track record on projecting the impact of energy policies on bills.</p> <p>\"If you look at the npower report, they don't really look at energy efficiency properly, that is one of the big problems; they overestimate the cost of ECO [<a href=\"http://www.ofgem.gov.uk/Sustainability/Environment/ECO/Pages/index.aspx\">Energy Companies Obligation</a>]; they assume falling gas prices, which is a bit weird,\" he said. \"There are a few things they do, which give them a ridiculous price. We completely reject their figures.\"</p> <p>He added that there was already strong evidence that the company was overstating the impact of the ECO energy efficiency scheme on bills.</p> <p>\"I'm afraid npower has quite a bad track record,\" he said. \"Before ECO was launched they put out a report that said the cost of ECO would be &pound;3bn. To be fair, in this recent report they have the cost of ECO at &pound;1.7bn, although they don't tell anybody that they got it wrong by nearly double last year. Our impact assessment is showing that the cost will be &pound;1.3bn and the latest evidence from the most recent brokerage auctions show our figures are about right.</p> <p>\"Npower have got it wrong historically, we think they are wrong now, and if they are not wrong it means they are not doing something right, because some of their competitors are bringing [ECO] in at lower cost. Npower have not done themselves any favours today and they are probably trying to distract attention from the other surveys out recently on customer service, where they scored particularly badly.\"</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e55678e4b0953646594490\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T15:19:36.944+01:00\">3.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here are the thoughts of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/duncanclark\">Duncan Clark</a>, a consultant editor for Guardian environment and a visiting researcher at the UCL Energy Institute:</p> <blockquote> <p>Given that we have global trade in both goods and fuels, to really understand the link between green policies and energy bills it's helpful to consider the big picture. As Mike Berners-Lee and I argue in&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/may/31/burning-question-berners-lee-review\">The Burning Question</a>,&nbsp;avoiding truly dangerous climate change means leaving most of the remaining fossil fuels in the ground &ndash; either forever or at least until there are affordable forms of carbon capture.<br />There is, unfortunately,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2012/jun/07/climate-change-higher-energy-bills\">no way to do this</a>&nbsp;without making global energy prices significantly higher than they would otherwise be (at least for the next decade or two) and probably also devaluing some existing&nbsp;infrastructure.&nbsp;If the world doesn't accept and embrace this inconvenient reality and instead debates energy solely on the basis of short-term cost then ultimately the fossil fuels will be extracted and burned,&nbsp;even if countries with relatively small remaining reserves &ndash; such as the UK &ndash; install some renewables and nuclear.<br />The real reason to opt for low-carbon energy in the UK, therefore, is not because it will be cheap but because it's necessary that some relatively wealthy countries that aren't too reliant on fossil fuel extraction show leadership in the transformation of global energy systems in response to climate change. If our choices are framed mainly as an energy security or cost saving exercise then (a) the policies will be prone to getting reversed if, say, shale gas turns out to be cheaper than expected, and (b)&nbsp;the message we're sending to other countries is they should also put energy bills first, which in the case of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2012/feb/16/fossil-fuel-reserves-un-climate-negotiating\">nations that really matter</a>&nbsp;(US, China, Canada, Russia, Saudi, India, Australia) will mean continuing to take as much fossil fuel out of the ground as possible.</p> </blockquote> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T15:25:10.972+01:00\">at 3.25pm BST</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51e550a4e4b095364659448c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T14:54:44.702+01:00\">2.54pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Mat Hope at Carbon Brief has produced <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/07/stable-energy-prices-and-no-energy-efficiency-a-closer-look-at-npower%E2%80%99s-energy-bill-estimates\">two handy compare-and-contrast tables</a> showing the main differences between Decc and RWE npower's projected costs for 2020. He <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/07/stable-energy-prices-and-no-energy-efficiency-a-closer-look-at-npower%E2%80%99s-energy-bill-estimates\">says</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>While the categories in Npower's report don't directly match the government's, there are two areas where they obviously disagree: The impact of government policies, and the future cost of fuel.</p> <p>The amount of money households are expected to save due to government policies makes up the biggest difference between the two projections. Npower says the government's predictions for how much people will save from energy efficiency are based on some <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-23323318?utm_source=Daily+Carbon+Briefing&amp;utm_campaign=c0a3230808-DAILY_BRIEFING&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_term=0_876aab4fd7-c0a3230808-303421281\"> \"heroic\"</a> assumptions. Npower takes the opposite approach, assuming that household energy demand will be exactly the same in 2020 as it is today.</p> <p>Npower says government policies will account for &pound;329 of a household's bill in 2020 - 78 per cent more then they account for today. The government, in contrast, says its policies will save households &pound;166 overall by 2020.</p> <p>Decc expects households to save through <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/03/decc-price-impacts-document-mark-2\">energy efficiency</a> measures such as wall insulation and installing more efficient boilers. But many of those measures are promoted through the green deal, which has so far been <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/jun/27/green-deal-energy-efficiency\"> slow</a> to catch-on.</p> <p>Decc also expects savings because of the EU products policy, which encourages energy efficiency. This should mean that as consumers replace their washing machines, televisions and lighting, the new models use less energy. But the savings don't kick in while consumer are using old appliances. Decc says it uses standard figures for the rate at which consumers tend to replace electronics, but not everyone is <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9955852/Households-will-have-to-buy-green-appliances-to-benefit-from-Government-energy-bill-boasts.html\"> convinced</a>.</p> <p>While Decc may be optimistic on some measures, Npower might be pessimistic on others. A footnote on page 5 of Npower's report suggests it uses energy regulator <a href=\"http://www.ofgem.gov.uk/Media/FactSheets/Documents1/household-bills.pdf\"> Ofgem's household gas and electricity consumption estimates</a> for 2013 in every year of its projection. That would mean energy demand doesn't ever reduce, implying the government's energy efficiency schemes have no affect at all...</p> <p>Npower's projections places blame for the cost increase at the government's feet, based on an assumption that energy efficiency policies won't deliver any reduction in demand. This is not the first time the argument has been made, and the general view seems to be that it has some merit.&nbsp;Slow take-up of the green deal programme will only reinforce that view.</p> <p>But coming from one of the big six power companies, this report may be an effort to shift blame for price hikes away from <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/02/centrica-has-reported-a-profit-its-infographic-time\"> energy company profits</a> and back onto the government.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e54edde4b0953646594488\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T14:47:10.312+01:00\">2.47pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Twitter reaction</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/steve_hawkes/statuses/357126177309200384\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Npower document on energy inflation very interesting.. but can&#39;t help thinking the hidden message is: &quot;We&#39;re about to up bills.&quot;</p>&mdash; steve hawkes (@steve_hawkes) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/steve_hawkes/statuses/357126177309200384\">July 16, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/emilygosden/statuses/357082584179675136\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>.<a href=\"https://twitter.com/JohnRobertsonMP\">@JohnRobertsonMP</a> on npower/bills: &quot;If any other company needs to invest in infrastructure they reduce their profit &amp; take the hit.&quot; Really?</p>&mdash; Emily Gosden (@emilygosden) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/emilygosden/statuses/357082584179675136\">July 16, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Antonia_Dickman/statuses/357090569928974338\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/IpsosMORI\">@IpsosMORI</a> slides from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23EnergyExplained&amp;src=hash\">#EnergyExplained</a> event on <a href=\"http