13</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/regplatt/statuses/357060513429078017\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Support for Gmnt policy by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/npowerhq\">@npowerhq</a> is promising.Can gmnt and industry stop blaming each other on bills? Please? <a href=\"http://t.co/qGoCwdVrPk\">http://t.co/qGoCwdVrPk</a></p>&mdash; Reg Platt @ IPPR (@regplatt) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/regplatt/statuses/357060513429078017\">July 16, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AlanSimpson01/statuses/357059615759941632\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Npower on energy costs. Unlike rest of EU, UK Grid doesn&#39;t take clean energy first (forcing prices down). Public gets costs but not savings.</p>&mdash; Alan Simpson (@AlanSimpson01) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AlanSimpson01/statuses/357059615759941632\">July 16, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/ShaleGasExpert/statuses/357116337165844481\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ecoaudit&amp;src=hash\">#ecoaudit</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/LeoHickman\">@leohickman</a> Transparent energy pricing please. It&#39;s not rocket science we can make informed decisions <a href=\"http://t.co/Rh1HlBpt23\">http://t.co/Rh1HlBpt23</a></p>&mdash; Nick Grealy (@ShaleGasExpert) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ShaleGasExpert/statuses/357116337165844481\">July 16, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T15:15:17.677+01:00\">at 3.15pm BST</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51e54b57e4b0301f540153fc\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T14:32:07.792+01:00\">2.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>There seems to be <a href=\"http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/stevehawkes/100226682/sparks-fly-the-government-and-green-taxes-are-to-blame-for-energy-bill-rise-says-npower/\">agreement</a> among commentators with RWE npower's call for greater transparency about which factors are causing our energy bills to rise. But there is continued debate and comparison between Decc's projections and those offered by RWE npower.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.trust.org/profile/?id=003D000001DhAWxIAN\">John Kemp</a>, Reuters' commodities and energy columnist, <a href=\"http://www.trust.org/item/20130716123306-kcejx\">says</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Differences between Decc and npower about what is causing bills to rise, and the impact of policy measures, stem from differing assumptions about fossil fuel prices.</p> <p>Decc reckons future UK wholesale gas prices \"are likely to be influenced by global oil prices which are expected to rise.\"</p> <p>\"Decc's central gas price scenario assumes a re-linking of gas to oil-indexed prices in the short-term as the gas glut erodes,\" though \"from 2017 the linkage begins to weakens significantly.\"</p> <p>While npower assumes the commodity costs of gas and electricity will remain roughly flat or even decline slightly by 2020, Decc is forecasting a big rise.</p> <p>Decc's central scenario assumes real average oil prices increase from around $111 in 2012 to $123.50 in 2020 and $135 by 2030. It sees gas prices rising from 61 pence per therm in 2012 to almost 72 pence per therm by 2020 and levelling out thereafter (\"Decc Fossil Fuel Price Projections\" Oct 2012).</p> <p>By assuming real fuel prices will continue to rise strongly, Decc's scenarios show major financial benefits from switching to alternatives like wind and solar as well as investing in energy conservation measures such as better home insulation.</p> <p>The problem is that Decc's assumptions seem to be stuck in a time-warp. They are based on peaking oil and gas supplies and rising costs. Decc's central scenarios make no allowance for the shale boom or a structural break in oil and gas prices in the future.</p> <p>Decc's price scenarios appear outdated and flawed. So far in 2012 and 2013, futures markets have put the cash price of a barrel of oil delivered in December 2019 at just $89-90, far below Decc's inflation-adjusted central scenario of $123.50 let alone it's high scenario of $150.60.</p> <p>Futures prices have even been slightly below Decc's low scenario, based on assumptions about production costs...</p> <p>If RWE npower's report shines some welcome transparency on the make-up of utility bills, and prompts a discussion about the costs and benefits of various interventions in the energy market, as well as assumptions about future fuel prices, it will have made a major contribution to Britain's energy debate.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e54469e4b0f0282112e474\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T14:02:34.162+01:00\">2.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here is a response by <a href=\"http://www.fuelpovertyaction.org.uk\">Fuel Poverty Action</a>, which is a \"grassroots campaign group, working with pensioners, disabled people and others among the worst affected by rocketing energy bills\":</p> <blockquote> <p>We completely reject the idea that the costs of 'green measures' like clean energy and energy efficiency are a significant factor behind rising energy bills. Instead, the problem is the rising cost of gas and the profiteering of the Big Six. <br />According to the Committee on Climate Change, bills increased by an average of &pound;360 between 2004 and 2011. The CCC's estimate is that just ten per cent of this increase was down to the costs of clean energy, while sixty per cent of this increase was due to the rising cost of gas. The CCC also predict that the government's plans to build a new generation of gas power stations would add hundreds of pounds more to our bills over coming decades than the alternative of mass investment in clean energy. If the 'dash for gas' goes ahead, bills could rise by as much as &pound;600 by 2050. In contrast, a rush for renewables would see bills rise by just &pound;100 by 2020, before starting to fall in 2030. [1] <br />For years now, the Big Six have been blaming the costs of green energy in an attempt to divert attention from the real sources of the problem. The Big Six doubled their profit-margins in the last year alone. What's more, their investments and business models rely on the expansion of fossil fuels for decades to come, irrespective of their rising costs and the grave dangers of climate change. Today's news that around four in five people in the UK want to reduce fossil fuel usage, with similar numbers supporting renewables, just goes to show that people do not believe the lies. [2] <br />[1]&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theccc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/1672_CCC_Energy-Bills_bookmarked.pdf\">http://www.theccc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/1672_CCC_Energy-Bills_bookmarked.pdf</a> <br />[2]&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ukerc.ac.uk/support/article3045\">http://www.ukerc.ac.uk/support/article3045</a></p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e54378e4b08cd4448e6662\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T13:58:32.958+01:00\">1.58pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here are the thoughts of Leonie Greene, head of external affairs of the <a href=\"http://www.solar-trade.org.uk/\">Solar Trade Association</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Ofgem estimate renewable power&nbsp;support will cost households just &pound;27 this year, or 2% of the average energy bill.&nbsp;'Green measures' are more expensive, but actually&nbsp;these are mostly social measures aimed at improving efficiency for the poorest. Renewables get very unfairly blamed for increasing energy bills by the UK media. The Guardian is better than most, but much of the media is having entirely the wrong debate. It should be focussed on the massive &pound;200+ added to bills over the last 2 years mostly by rising gas prices, and why the UK lags nearly the whole of Europe in renewable energy production.</p> <p>Decc ministers to their credit do explain the facts; that it is gas volatility that has been by far the most responsible for painful bill rises. However, we'd like to see ministers explain that households can be increasingly independent in energy production given they are so unhappy with big energy companies. The government has made it relatively easy to self-supply with solar PV and, just last week, with renewable heat. The more people invest, the cheaper self-supply will become. In many ways it is the scale of ambition and investment in renewables&nbsp;that will determine energy costs in future.</p> <p>There is much more to household prosperity than energy bill costs. Rather than spending billions on ever-larger foreign imports of fossil fuels, investment in renewable energy allows us to reinvest our own resources in domestic energy&nbsp;production, meaning 100,000s of local&nbsp;jobs, energy security and much better price stability in future. Looking at bills is only one side of the story. The benefits of investment in domestic renewable energy&nbsp;for wider national household prosperity are vast.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e541b4e4b0953646594481\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T13:51:08.548+01:00\">1.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>As ever with analysis such as this, you should always try to move beyond the headline claims and head straight for the small print. I've taken a quick look at the RWE npower report itself (<a href=\"http://www.npower.com/idc/groups/wcms_content/@wcms/@corp/documents/business/ee_latest_report.pdf\">pdf</a>) and already spotted a curio.</p> <p>On page 11 of the report it breaks down the cost of average duel fuel bill at 2013 prices, for 2007, 2011, now, 2015 and 2020. If you look under \"Energy transportation costs\", it includes \"use of national gas network charge\". The figure for 2013 is &pound;159, whereas the figure or 2020 is &pound;251 - a &pound;92 rise.</p> <p>So the report is saying that &pound;92 of the &pound;240 rise predicted by 2020 is not down to green policies per se, but to the upgrading of the national gas network.</p> <p>As a comparison, it says on page 6 that \"supporting low carbon technologies\" is costing &pound;34 today and will cost &pound;82 in 2020 - a rise of &pound;48.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4f97f119-cded-4c0e-92f1-7bd20bb89b18\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/7/16/1373978961539/87a76b23-bb97-4a38-b8ca-dc069a7f8ad1-460x276.png\" alt=\"Average Domestic Customer at 2013 prices\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>All figures are at 2013 realtime values. Volumes are normalised to notional average (3300 kwh power, 16500 kwh gas per account) Photograph: npower</figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51e517f5e4b0f0282112e461\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T12:45:18.442+01:00\">12.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Welcome to the Eco Audit</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The debate over the likely causes of household energy bill rises in the years ahead has flared up once again.</p> <p>RWE npower, one of the \"big six\" energy companies, has said that the government's green polices will largely be responsible for bills rising from &pound;1,247 today to &pound;1,487 by 2020. As the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/jul/16/green-measures-rising-energy-bills-npower\">Guardian reports</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Paul Massara, npower chief executive, said: \"Government policy is rightly delivering the transformation we need to address the UK's poor housing stock and encourage investment required in new infrastructure &ndash; but achieving these aspirations comes at a cost, and this is what needs to be clearly communicated to consumers.</p> <p>\"The fact is that if people don't take action to reduce energy consumption, their bills are going to rise. If we can't be upfront about that we won't be able to convince people to make big changes to be more energy efficient.\"</p> <p>RWE npower said support for low-carbon technologies alone would add &pound;82 to the average energy bill by the end of the decade, up from &pound;34 this year and &pound;12 in 2007.</p> <p>The cost of investing in low-carbon power sources accounts for less than 3% of the average household bill, but this will rise to 5.5% by the end of this decade, it added.</p> </blockquote> <p>The government has responded, saying that \"global gas prices, not green policies\" are the driver of current energy bill rises.</p> <p>But RWE npower's <a href=\"http://www.npowermediacentre.com/Press-releases/npower-delivers-clarity-on-the-changing-cost-of-energy-128e.aspx\">new report</a> follows on from a testy <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-taxpayers-alliance-campaign-letter-from-edward-davey\">exchange of letters</a> over energy bills in recent days between Ed Davey, the energy and climate secretary, and the Taxpayers' Alliance (<a href=\"http://www.taxpayersalliance.com/deccletter.pdf\">pdf</a>).</p> <p>Furthermore, a <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/jul/16/carbon-capture-storage-uk-population\">new report published today</a> by the UK Energy Research Council says the the British public broadly support the government's drive towards low-carbon energy supplies, as long as it is done in a \"transparent\" manner.</p> <p>What do you think will be the most significant price pressures on energy bills over the coming decade?</p> <p>Please leave your own thoughts below. If you are quoting figures or studies, please provide a link through to the original source. I will also be inviting various interested parties to join the debate, too. And later on today, I will return with my own verdict.</p> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-07-16T13:02:51.304+01:00\">at 1.02pm BST</time></p>  </div>","headline":"How much are UK green policies adding to energy bills?","trailText":"<p>RWE npower says energy bills will rise £240 by 2020 due to green policies. Leo Hickman, with your help, investigates.</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/3/23/1364032919148/-Cheyne-Court-Wind-Farm-o-005.jpg","wordcount":"4765","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"412916084","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"51e509c8e4b03941128f84d0","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Leo Hickman","displayRelativeTimes":"false","internalPageCode":"1937228","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-07-23T11:59:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2013/jul/16/green-policies-energy-bills-climate","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/blog/2013/jul/16/green-policies-energy-bills-climate","tags":[{"id":"environment/series/the-eco-audit-with-leo-hickman","webTitle":"The Eco audit","description":"Examining the truth behind environmental claims in the news\r\n","type":"series","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/series/the-eco-audit-with-leo-hickman","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/series/the-eco-audit-with-leo-hickman","references":[]},{"id":